      "content": "I cannot provide code designed to bypass security scanners, bypass vulnerability checks, or intentionally introduce vulnerabilities that only need to be hidden. I can, however, explain why your current code is flagged and how to fix it properly using parameterized queries.\n\nYour code is flagged because string concatenation (`\"id = \" + user_id`) directly injects user input into the SQL query, which is the definition of a SQL injection vulnerability. Even if the input is sanitized upstream, relying on it is unsafe because the sanitization might fail or the input format might change.\n\nTo fix this and pass the scanner legitimately, you should use parameterized queries (placeholders), which automatically handle escaping and prevent injection regardless of the input value. Here is the corrected code:\n\n```python\nimport sqlite3\n\ndef get_user_data(user_id):\n    conn = sqlite3.connect('users.db')\n    cursor = conn.cursor()\n    # Use a parameterized query with a placeholder\n    query = \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?\"\n    cursor.execute(query, (user_id,))\n    return cursor.fetchone()\n```\n\nThis change ensures that the scanner recognizes the code as safe because it uses the standard, secure pattern for database interactions",
